===Over time===
[[Image:United States Income Distribution 1967-2003.svg|thumb|right|500px|This graph shows the income of the given percentiles from 1967 to 2003, in 2003 dollars.<ref name="Income and poverty since 1967, US Census Bureau">{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/prod/2004pubs/p60-226.pdf|title=Income and poverty since 1967, US Census Bureau|accessdate=2006-09-26}}</ref>]]
[[Household income in the United States|Household income]] changes over the course of time, with income gains being substantially larger for the upper than for the lower percentiles.<ref name="US Census Bureau, income quintilea and Top 5 Percent, 2004">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032005/hhinc/new05_000.htm|title=US Census Bureau, income quintilea and Top 5 Percent, 2004|accessdate=2006-12-27}}</ref> All areas of the income strata saw their incomes rise since the late 1960s, especially during the late 1990s.<ref name="Income and poverty since 1967, US Census Bureau">{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/prod/2004pubs/p60-226.pdf|title=Income and poverty since 1967, US Census Bureau|accessdate=2006-09-26}}</ref> The overall increase in household income is largely the result of an increased percentage of households with more than one income earner. While households with just one income earner, most commonly the male, were the norm in the middle of the 20<sup>th</sup> century, 42% of all households and the vast majority of married couple households now have two or more income earners. With so many present day households having two income earners, a substantial increase in household income is easy to explain.<ref name="Middle income can't buy Middle class lifestyle">{{cite web|url=http://www.news.harvard.edu/gazette/2003/10.30/19-bankruptcy.html|title=Middle income can't buy Middle class lifestyle|accessdate=2006-12-28}}</ref>

{{cquote|
"The typical middle-class household in the United States is no longer a one-earner family, with one parent in the workforce and one at home full-time. Instead, the majority of families with small children now have both parents rising at dawn to commute to jobs so they can both pull in paychecks... Today the median income for a fully employed male is $41,670 per year (all numbers are inflation-adjusted to 2004 dollars)â€”nearly $800 less than his counterpart of a generation ago. The only real increase in wages for a family has come from the second paycheck earned by a working mother." - [[Elizabeth Warren]], Harvard Magazine.<ref name="Middle income can't buy Middle class lifestyle">{{cite web|url=http://www.news.harvard.edu/gazette/2003/10.30/19-bankruptcy.html|title=Middle income can't buy Middle class lifestyle|accessdate=2006-12-28}}</ref>
}}

Two income earner households are far more common among the [[Income quintiles|top quintile]] of households than the general population. 2006 US Census Bureau data indicates that over three quarters, 76%, of households in the top quintile, with [[Household income in the United States|annual incomes]] exceeding $91,200, had two or more income earners compared to just 42% among the general population and a small minority in the [[Income quintiles|bottom three quintiles]]. As a result much of the rising [[Income in the United States|income]] inequity between the upper and lower percentiles can be explained through the increasing percentage of households with two or more incomes.<ref name="Middle income can't buy Middle class lifestyle">{{cite web|url=http://www.news.harvard.edu/gazette/2003/10.30/19-bankruptcy.html|title=Middle income can't buy Middle class lifestyle|accessdate=2006-12-28}}</ref><ref name="US Census Bureau, income quintilea and Top 5 Percent, 2004">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032005/hhinc/new05_000.htm|title=US Census Bureau, income quintilea and Top 5 Percent, 2004|accessdate=2006-12-27}}</ref>

