==Median income levels==
{{see|Personal income in the United States|Household income in the United States}}
{{Income in the US}}

==Professions==
[[Image:Income profession.png|thumb|300px|Median annual earnings of selected professions as well as the nation medain income of full-time, year-round employed workers, according to the US Department of Labor.]]
The vast majority of Americans derive the majority of their income from occupational earnings. <ref> name="Occupation and Class Consciousness in America">{{cite book | last = Eichar | first = Douglas | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 1989 | title = Occupation and Class Consciousness in America | publisher = Greenwood Press | location = Westport, Connecticut | id = 0-313-26111-3}}</ref> [[Income in the United States|Income]] derived from an occupation is largely determined by scarcity and the economic law of [[supply and demand]]. The more demand for a certain specialty and the less supply, the higher the income. There has been shown to be a correlation between increases in income and increases in worker satisfaction. The decrease in worker dissatisfaction, however, is not solely a result of the increase in income. Workers in more complex and [[Social structure of the United States|higher level]] occupations tend to have [[Educational attainment in the United States|attained higher levels of education]] and thus are more likely to have a greater degree of autonomy in the workplace.<ref name="Occupation and Class Consciousness in America">{{cite book | last = Eichar | first = Douglas | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 1989 | title = Occupation and Class Consciousness in America | publisher = Greenwood Press | location = Westport, Connecticut | id = 0-313-26111-3}}</ref> Additionally higher level workers with advanced degrees are hired to share their personal knowledge, to conceptualize, and to consult. Higher-level workers suffer less job alienation and reap not only external benefits in terms of income from their jobs, but also enjoy high levels of intrinsic motivation and satisfaction.<ref name="Society in Focus">{{cite book | last = Thompson | first = William | authorlink = | coauthors = Joseph Hickey | year = 2005 | title = Society in Focus | publisher = Pearson | location = Boston, MA| id = 0-205-41365-X}}</ref><ref name="Occupation and Class Consciousness in America">{{cite book | last = Eichar | first = Douglas | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 1989 | title = Occupation and Class Consciousness in America | publisher = Greenwood Press | location = Westport, Connecticut | id = 0-313-26111-3}}</ref>

In the United States the highest earning occupational groups were [[American middle class#Professional/Managerial middle class|White collar professionals]] including management. Individuals in these occupations tend to experience the highest job satisfaction and highest incomes. The overall highest paying profession in the United States is that of physician. <ref name="Society in Focus">{{cite book | last = Thompson | first = William | authorlink = | coauthors = Joseph Hickey | year = 2005 | title = Society in Focus | publisher = Pearson | location = Boston, MA| id = 0-205-41365-X}}</ref> Physician (M.D.and D.O.) compensation ranks as the highest median annual earnings of any profession. Median annual earnings ranged from $156,010 for family physicians to $321,686 for [[anesthesiologists]]. Surgeons post a median annual income of $282,504.<ref name="US Department of Labor, annual earnings for doctors">{{cite web|url=http://www.bls.gov/oco/ocos074.htm#earnings|title=US Department of Labor, annual earnings for doctors|accessdate=2006-12-27}}</ref> By comparison the median annual salary for a Chief Executive Officer (C.E.O.) in May 2004 was $140,350.<ref name="US Department of Labor, CEO salaries">{{cite web|url=http://www.bls.gov/oco/ocos012.htm#earnings|title=US Department of Labor, CEO salaries|accessdate=2006-12-27}}</ref> Overall annual earnings among the nation's top 25 professions ranged from the $70,000s to the $300,000s. In addition to physicians, lawyers, physicists, air traffic controllers, and nuclear engineers were all among the nation's 20 highest paid occupations with incomes in excess of $78,410.<ref name="Bureau of Labor statistics data published by Monster.com, 20 highest paying jobs">{{cite web|url=http://content.salary.monster.com/articles/salary/highestpay/|title=Bureau of Labor statistics data published by Monster.com, 20 highest paying jobs|accessdate=2006-12-27}}</ref> Some of the other occupations in the high five-figure range were economists with a median of $72,780<ref name="US Department of Labor, median income of Economists">{{cite web|url=http://www.bls.gov/oco/ocos055.htm#earnings|title=US Department of Labor, median income of Economists|accessdate=2006-12-27}}</ref>, mathematicians with $81,240<ref name="US Department of Labor, median income of Mathematicians">{{cite web|url=http://www.bls.gov/oco/ocos043.htm#earnings|title=US Department of Labor, median income of Mathematicians|accessdate=2006-12-27}}</ref>, financial managers with $81,880,<ref name="US Department of Labor, median income of financial managers">{{cite web|url=http://www.bls.gov/oco/ocos010.htm#earnings|title=US Department of Labor, median income of financial managers|accessdate=2006-12-27}}</ref> and software publishers with median annual earnings of $73,060.<ref name="US Department of Labor, median income of Software Publishers">{{cite web|url=http://www.bls.gov/oco/ocos110.htm#earnings|title=US Department of Labor, median income of Software Publishers|accessdate=2006-12-27}}</ref>

==Education==
[[Image:Education median income.png|thumb|325px|Median [[Household income in the United States|household]] and [[Personal income in the United States|personal income]] by [[Educational attainment in the United States|educational attainment]].]]
{{see|Educational attainment in the United States}}
[[Educational attainment in the United States|Educational attainment]] plays a major factor in determining an individual's economic disposition. Personal income varied greatly according to an individual's education, as did household income. Incomes for those employed, full-time, year-round and over the age of twenty-five ranged from $20,826 ($17,422 if including those who worked part-time<ref name="US Census Bureau, personal income distribution, age 25+, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/perinc/new03_001.htm|title=US Census Bureau, personal income distribution, age 25+, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-28}}</ref>) for those with less than a ninth grade education to $100,000 for those with professional degrees ($82,473 if including those who work part-time<ref name="US Census Bureau, personal income distribution, age 25+, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/perinc/new03_001.htm|title=US Census Bureau, personal income distribution, age 25+, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-28}}</ref>). This median income for individuals with doctorates was $79,401 ($70,853 if including those who work part-time<ref name="US Census Bureau, personal income distribution, age 25+, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/perinc/new03_001.htm|title=US Census Bureau, personal income distribution, age 25+, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-28}}</ref>).<ref name="US Census Bureau, personal income for full-time, year round employed employed workers, age 25+">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/perinc/new03_010.htm|title=US Census Bureau, personal income for full-time, year round employed employed workers, age 25+|accessdate=2006-12-28}}</ref> These statistics reveal that the majority of those employed full-time with professional or doctoral degrees are among the overall top 10% (15% if including those who work part time) of income earners. Of those with a master's degree, nearly 50% were among the top quarter of income earners (top third if including those who work part time).<ref name="US Census Bureau, personal income distribution, age 25+, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/perinc/new03_001.htm|title=US Census Bureau, personal income distribution, age 25+, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-28}}</ref>

==Race==
[[Image:Race 6 figure household and.png|thumb|250px|Percent of households with six figure incomes and individuals with incomes in the top 10%, exceeding $77,500.]]
[[Image:Race Six Figure Household Income.png|thumb|250px|Racial breakdown of households with [[six figure income]]s.]]

Recent US Census Bureau publications indicate a strong correlation between race and affluence. In the top [[Household income in the United States|household income]] quintile, households with incomes exceeding $91,200, [[White American|Whites]] and [[Asian American]]s were overrepresented, whereas Hispanics and [[African American]]s were underrepresented. The household income for Asian Americans was, at $61,094, by far the highest,<ref name="US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Asians, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/hhinc/new02_008.htm|title=US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Asians, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> exceeding that of Whites ($48,554) by 26%.<ref name="US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Whites">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/hhinc/new02_003.htm|title=US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Whites|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> Over a quarter, 27.5%, of Asian American households had incomes exceeding $100,000 , and another 40% had incomes of over $75,000.<ref name="US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Whites, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/hhinc/new02_008.htm|title=US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Whites, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> Among White households, who remained near the national median, 18.3% had six figure incomes, while 28.9% had incomes exceeding $75,000.<ref name="US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Whites">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/hhinc/new02_003.htm|title=US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Whites|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> The percentages of households with incomes exceeding $100,000 and $75,000 were far below the national medians for Hispanic and African American households.<ref name="US Census Bureau, household income distribution for African Americans">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/hhinc/new02_006.htm|title=US Census Bureau, household income distribution for African Americans|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> Among Hispanic households, for example, only 9% had six figure incomes, and 17% had incomes exceeding $75,000.<ref name="US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Hispanics, 2006">{{Cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/hhinc/new02_009.htm|title=US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Hispanics, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> The race gap remained when considering personal income. In 2005, roughly 11% of Asian Americans<ref name="US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for Asian Americans, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/hhinc/new02_009.htm|title=US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for Asian Americans, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> and 7% of White individuals<ref name="US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for Whites, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/perinc/new03_002.htm|title=US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for Whites, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> had [[six figure income]]s, compared to 2.6% among Hispanics<ref name="US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for Hispanics, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/perinc/new03_009.htm|title=US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for Hispanics, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> and 2.3% among African Americans.<ref name="US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for African Americans, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/perinc/new03_005.htm|title=US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for African Americans, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref>

The racial breakdowns of income brackets further illustrate the racial disparities associated with affluence. in 2005, 81.8% of all 114 million households were [[White American|White]],<ref name="US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Whites">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/hhinc/new02_003.htm|title=US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Whites|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> 12.2% were [[African American]],<ref name="US Census Bureau, household income distribution for African Americans">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/hhinc/new02_006.htm|title=US Census Bureau, household income distribution for African Americans|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> 10.9% were Hispanic<ref name="US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Hispanics, 2006">{{Cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/hhinc/new02_009.htm|title=US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Hispanics, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> and 3.7% were [[Asian American]].<ref name="US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Asians, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/hhinc/new02_008.htm|title=US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Asians, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref><ref name="US Census Bureau, overall households income distribution to $100,000, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/hhinc/new02_001.htm|title=US Census Bureau, overall households income distribution to $100,000, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> While White households are always near the [[Household income in the United States|national median]] due to Whites being the by far most prevalent racial demographic, the percentages of minority households with incomes exceeding $100,000 strayed considerably from their percentage of the overall population. [[Asian American#Income|Asian Americans]], who represent the smallest surveyed racial demographic in the overall population, were the found to be the prevalent minority among six figure income households. Among the nearly twenty million households with six figure incomes, 86.9% were White,<ref name="US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Whites">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/hhinc/new02_003.htm|title=US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Whites|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> 5.9% were Asian American,<ref name="US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Asians, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/hhinc/new02_008.htm|title=US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Asians, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> 5.6% were Hispanic<ref name="US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Hispanics, 2006">{{Cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/hhinc/new02_009.htm|title=US Census Bureau, household income distribution for Hispanics, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> and 5.5% were African American.<ref name="US Census Bureau, household income distribution for African Americans">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/hhinc/new02_006.htm|title=US Census Bureau, household income distribution for African Americans|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> Among the general individual population '''''with earnings''''', 82.1% were White,<ref name="US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for Whites, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/perinc/new03_002.htm|title=US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for Whites, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> 12.7% were Hispanic,<ref name="US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for Hispanics, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/perinc/new03_009.htm|title=US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for Hispanics, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> 11.0% were African American<ref name="US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for African Americans, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/perinc/new03_005.htm|title=US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for African Americans, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> and 4.6% were Asian American.<ref name="US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for Asian Americans, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/hhinc/new02_009.htm|title=US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for Asian Americans, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> Of the top 10% of income earners, those nearly 15 million individuals with incomes exceeding $77,500, Whites and Asians were once again overrepresented with the percentages of African Americans and Hispanics trailing behind considerably. Of the top 10% of earners, 86.7% were White.<ref name="US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for Whites, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/perinc/new03_002.htm|title=US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for Whites, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> Asian Americans were the prevalent minority, constituting 6.8% of top 10% income earners, nearly twice the percentage of Asian Americans among the general population.<ref name="US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for Asian Americans, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/hhinc/new02_009.htm|title=US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for Asian Americans, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref> Hispanics, who were the prevalent minority in the general population of [[Personal income in the United States|income earners]], constituted only 5.2% of those in the top 10%<ref name="US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for Hispanics, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/perinc/new03_009.htm|title=US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for Hispanics, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref>, with African Americans being the least represented with 5.1%.<ref name="US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for African Americans, 2006">{{cite web|url=http://pubdb3.census.gov/macro/032006/perinc/new03_005.htm|title=US Census Bureau, personal income distribution for African Americans, 2006|accessdate=2006-12-29}}</ref>

